      "body" : "Why does Java need this .class property anyways? Why can&#39;t you just reference the class as &quot;Print&quot;, as it is possible in JavaScript?"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 498110,
        "reputation" : 1420,
        "user_id" : 1377112,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 57,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/MhEcS.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Salvador Valencia",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1377112/salvador-valencia"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1651870668,
      "post_id" : 15078951,
      "comment_id" : 127476131,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Having access to just the Class (not an instance) allows you at least to call its public Static methods and Static attributes. Lets say you create a Static method that calculates a local tax value, so you would call the method directly form the LocalTax Class: LocalTax.calcTax(myValue);"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1359686,
      "reputation" : 12427,
      "user_id" : 1297272,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/j3H9xcFd.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Javier",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1297272/javier"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 200,
    "last_activity_date" : 1663142827,
    "last_edit_date" : 1663142827,
    "creation_date" : 1361837001,
    "answer_id" : 15078951,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>When you write <code>.class</code> after a class name, it references the class literal -\n<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>java.lang.Class</code></a> object that represents information <em>about</em> a given class.</p>\n<p>For example, if your class is <code>Print</code>, then <code>Print.class</code> is an object that represents the class <code>Print</code> on runtime. It is the same object that is returned by the <code>getClass()</code> method of any (direct) instance of <code>Print</code>.</p>\n<pre><code>Print myPrint = new Print();\nSystem.out.println(Print.class.getName());\nSystem.out.println(myPrint.getClass().getName());\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2009857,
        "reputation" : 26235,
        "user_id" : 1798593,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/be41e365336e709f1bfc2c9866eac8e9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Patricia Shanahan",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1798593/patricia-shanahan"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 10,
      "creation_date" : 1361837919,
      "post_id" : 15079000,
      "comment_id" : 21207640,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "<code>getClass()</code> is only useful if you have a reference pointing to an object of the class. <code>ClassName.class</code> can be used even if the class has no instances. For example, consider <code>Math.class</code>. Each is correct for certain situations."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 10018444,
        "reputation" : 6385,
        "user_id" : 7408927,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 75,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c916066d00e5c9c5f26b65d532754191?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Sevastyan Savanyuk",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7408927/sevastyan-savanyuk"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 2,
      "creation_date" : 1502791389,
      "post_id" : 15079000,
      "comment_id" : 78338758,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Brilliant explanation. Right to the point of it.Love how you identified the distinction between <code>.class</code> and <code>.getClass().</code>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2103622,
      "reputation" : 27446,
      "user_id" : 1870555,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/p5Q02.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "christopher",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1870555/christopher"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 77,
    "last_activity_date" : 1591518449,
    "last_edit_date" : 1591518449,
    "creation_date" : 1361837334,
    "answer_id" : 15079000,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>.class</code> is used when there isn't an instance of the class available.</p>\n\n<p><code>.getClass()</code> is used when there is an instance of the class available.</p>\n\n<p><code>object.getClass()</code> returns the class of the given object.</p>\n\n<p>For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String string = \"hello\";\nSystem.out.println(string.getClass().toString());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This will output:</p>\n\n<pre><code>class java.lang.String\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This is the class of the string object :)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 220105,
        "reputation" : 17645,
        "user_id" : 477349,
        "user_type" : "registered",
