      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "<code>in a fully object-oriented language, a Class is also an Object</code>?  &lt;citation needed&gt;"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2780043,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 2392744,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5b8f658bd340ca36ec159d9f5abbbaa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Xerxes",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2392744/xerxes"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1417729666,
    "last_edit_date" : 1417729666,
    "creation_date" : 1417721691,
    "answer_id" : 27302481,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I think the key here is understanding the difference between a Class and an Object.  An Object is an instance of a Class.  But in a fully object-oriented language, a <strong>Class is also an Object</strong>.  So calling <code>.class</code> gets the reference to the Class object of that Class, which can then be manipulated.</p>\n"
