    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If an instance of an object is available, then the simplest way to get its Class is to invoke <code>Object.getClass()</code></p>\n\n<p>The <code>.class</code> Syntax</p>\n\n<p>If the type is available but there is no instance then it is possible to obtain a Class by appending <code>.class</code> to the name of the type. This is also the easiest way to obtain the Class for a primitive type.</p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean b;\nClass c = b.getClass();   // compile-time error\n\nClass c = boolean.class;  // correct\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>See: <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/reflect/class/classNew.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">docs.oracle.com about class</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7918103,
      "reputation" : 166,
      "user_id" : 5979925,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8a8b35065f39d50415e825f2766d4eb5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ranjeet",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5979925/ranjeet"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1462275086,
    "creation_date" : 1462275086,
    "answer_id" : 37002946,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If there is no instance available then <code>.class</code> syntax is used to get the corresponding Class object for a class otherwise you can use getClass() method to get Class object. Since, there is no instance of primitive data type, we have to use <code>.class</code> syntax for primitive data types.</p>\n\n<pre><code>    package test;\n\n    public class Test {\n       public static void main(String[] args)\n       {\n          //there is no instance available for class Test, so use Test.class\n          System.out.println(\"Test.class.getName() ::: \" + Test.class.getName());\n\n          // Now create an instance of class Test use getClass()\n          Test testObj = new Test();\n          System.out.println(\"testObj.getClass().getName() ::: \" + testObj.getClass().getName());\n\n          //For primitive type\n          System.out.println(\"boolean.class.getName() ::: \" + boolean.class.getName());\n          System.out.println(\"int.class.getName() ::: \" + int.class.getName());\n          System.out.println(\"char.class.getName() ::: \" + char.class.getName());\n          System.out.println(\"long.class.getName() ::: \" + long.class.getName());\n       }\n    }\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 498110,
      "reputation" : 1420,
      "user_id" : 1377112,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 57,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/MhEcS.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Salvador Valencia",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1377112/salvador-valencia"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1474399102,
    "creation_date" : 1474399102,
    "answer_id" : 39602167,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just to clarify, this '.class' method is not referring to the bytecode file you see after compiling java code nor a confusion between the concepts of Class vs. Object in OOP theory.</p>\n\n<p>This '.class' method is used in Java for code Reflection. Generally you can gather meta data for your class such as the full qualified class name, list of constants, list of public fields, etc, etc.</p>\n\n<p>Check these links (already mentioned above) to get all the details:<br>\n<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/reflect/class/classNew.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/reflect/class/classNew.html</a><br>\n<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html</a></p>\n\n<p>Normally you don't plan on using Reflection right away when you start building your project. It's something that you know you need after trying to manage already working code. Many times you need it to manage multiple instances of your program. Maybe you want to identify each particular 'clone' to determine if something is already defined, or count the number of functions, or just simply log the details of a particular instance of your class.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1482474,
      "reputation" : 7633,
      "user_id" : 1652451,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/zwK34.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "PbxMan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1652451/pbxman"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1476349373,
    "creation_date" : 1476349373,
    "answer_id" : 40016621,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>A class literal is an expression consisting of the name of a class, interface, array, or primitive type, or the pseudo-type void, followed by a '.' and the token class.\nOne of the changes in JDK 5.0 is that the class java.lang.Class is generic, <code>java.lang.Class Class&lt;T&gt;</code>, therefore: </p>\n\n<pre><code>Class&lt;Print&gt; p = Print.class;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>References here:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/extra/generics/literals.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/extra/generics/literals.html</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.8.2\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.8.2</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5677475,
      "reputation" : 1368,
      "user_id" : 4490081,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1eea7948aafac7de81d4f198732d985f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "SRaj",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4490081/sraj"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1609862038,
    "last_edit_date" : 1609862038,
    "creation_date" : 1609573239,
    "answer_id" : 65536977,
    "question_id" : 15078935,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Adding to the above answers:</p>\n<p>Suppose you have a a class named &quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;. Assuming that is in classpath, the following statements are equivalent.</p>\n<pre><code>//checking class name using string comparison, only Runtime check possible\nif(myInstance.getClass().getName().equals(Class.forName(&quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;)).getName()){}\n\n//checking actual Class object for equality, only Runtime check possible\nif(myInstance.getClass().getName() == Class.forName(&quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;))){}\n\n//checking actual Class object for equality, but compile time validation\n//will ensure MyClass is in classpath. Hence this approach is better (according to fail-fast paradigm)\nif(myInstance.getClass() == MyClass.class){}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Similarly, the following are also equivalent.</p>\n<pre><code>Class&lt;?&gt; myClassObject = MyClass.class; //compile time check\n\nClass&lt;?&gt; myClassObject = Class.forname(&quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;); //only runtime check\n</code></pre>\n<p>If JVM loads a type, a class object representing that type will be present in JVM. we can get the metadata regarding the type from that class object which is used very much in reflection package. MyClass.class is a shorthand method which actually points to the Class object representing MyClass.</p>\n<p>As an addendum, some information about Class&lt;?&gt; reference which will be useful to read along with this as most of the time, they are used together.</p>\n<p>Class&lt;?&gt; reference type can hold any Class object which represents any type.</p>\n<p>This works in a similar fashion if the Class&lt;?&gt; reference is in method argument as well.</p>\n<p>Please note that the class &quot;Class&quot; does not have a public constructor. So you cannot instantiate &quot;Class&quot; instances with &quot;new&quot; operator.</p>\n"
  } ],
